HEADWORD: grotto
<hw>grot"to</hw> <pr>(gr⟦ocr⟧t"t⟦osl⟧)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>;
<plu><it>pl.</it> <plw>Grottoes</plw>
<pr>(gr⟦ocr⟧t"t⟦omac⟧z)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[Formerly <ets>grotta</ets>,
fr. It. <ets>grotta</ets>, LL. <ets>grupta</ets>, fr. L.
<ets>crypta</ets> a concealed subterranean passage, vault, cavern, Gr.
<grk>kry`pth</grk>, fr. <grk>krypto`s</grk> concealed, fr.
<grk>kry`ptein</grk> to conceal. Cf. <er>Grot</er>,
<er>Crypt</er>.]</ety> <def>A natural covered opening in the earth; a
cave; also, an artificial recess, cave, or cavernlike
apartment.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

